WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:06.080 --> 00:00:11.760
Hi from Tokyo, Japan, and welcome to Jeremy's IT&nbsp;
Lab. This video is about the Internet Protocol&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:11.760 --> 00:00:17.600
Suite, often called TCP/IP, the family of&nbsp;
protocols that makes communication over the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:17.600 --> 00:00:22.400
Internet and other networks possible. You've&nbsp;
probably heard of some of these protocols:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:22.400 --> 00:00:29.440
IP, TCP, UDP, HTTP and so on. If you&nbsp;
haven't heard of them, no problem:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:29.440 --> 00:00:32.640
we'll cover many of these&nbsp;
core protocols in this course.

00:00:32.640 --> 00:00:38.080
From this suite of protocols, we can build&nbsp;
what people usually call the TCP/IP model:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:38.080 --> 00:00:43.120
a way of grouping protocols into layers based&nbsp;
on the job they do. In this video we’re going&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:43.120 --> 00:00:48.880
to build that model step by step and use it as&nbsp;
a simple map of “who does what” in a network.

00:00:48.880 --> 00:00:52.800
This is going to be one of the longest videos&nbsp;
in the course, but there actually isn’t a lot&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:52.800 --> 00:00:58.880
you have to memorize: we’re covering a big-picture&nbsp;
framework about how networks work. Later, when you&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:00:58.880 --> 00:01:04.960
learn about things like IP addressing, routing and&nbsp;
switching, TCP and UDP, and so on, you’ll be able&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:04.960 --> 00:01:10.560
to drop each new topic into this framework and see&nbsp;
where it fits and how it works with the others.

00:01:10.560 --> 00:01:14.240
There’s also a lot of history - and a bit&nbsp;
of argument - around different models,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:14.240 --> 00:01:20.400
like the OSI model and various versions of the&nbsp;
TCP/IP model. In this lesson I’ll give you a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:20.400 --> 00:01:25.360
practical way to think about layers that will&nbsp;
help you understand how networks actually operate.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:25.360 --> 00:01:30.080
As you continue studying, you can add nuance&nbsp;
and explore the debates if you’re interested,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:30.080 --> 00:01:32.640
but you don’t need to solve those issues today.

00:01:32.640 --> 00:01:37.120
So, relax, don’t worry about memorizing&nbsp;
every concept, and just focus on the big&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:37.120 --> 00:01:41.120
ideas and relationships between the&nbsp;
layers. We’ll revisit these concepts&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:41.120 --> 00:01:46.240
many times in later videos. Alright,&nbsp;
enough talking. let’s get started.

00:01:46.240 --> 00:01:50.160
Let’s begin with the importance&nbsp;
of protocols and standards.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:50.160 --> 00:01:55.040
A protocol is a set of rules defining how data&nbsp;
should be communicated between devices over&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:01:55.040 --> 00:02:00.960
a network. Protocols are the languages that&nbsp;
computers use to communicate. Just as someone&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:00.960 --> 00:02:06.480
who only speaks Chinese can’t talk with someone&nbsp;
who only speaks English, computers that “speak”&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:06.480 --> 00:02:12.480
different protocols can’t exchange data. Since the&nbsp;
early days of computer networking, there have been&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:12.480 --> 00:02:17.440
several attempts to define the functions needed&nbsp;
for computers to communicate with each other.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:17.440 --> 00:02:23.040
These protocols were often developed by a specific&nbsp;
vendor, such as IBM, to be used with their own&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:23.040 --> 00:02:28.800
products. With this proprietary approach, enabling&nbsp;
communications between different vendors’ products&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:28.800 --> 00:02:35.600
was difficult, if not impossible. For example,&nbsp;
if we have an Apple iMac and an IBM server,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:35.600 --> 00:02:40.720
each using its own proprietary protocols,&nbsp;
the IBM server wouldn’t be able to understand&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:40.720 --> 00:02:46.240
a request from the iMac. I’m just using&nbsp;
modern devices here as a visual example,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:46.240 --> 00:02:51.360
but this kind of problem was common in the&nbsp;
early days of networking. To solve this issue,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:51.360 --> 00:02:56.480
today’s networks and the devices connected to&nbsp;
them use standard, vendor-neutral protocols and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:02:56.480 --> 00:03:02.720
technologies. A standard is an agreed-upon&nbsp;
specification that describes how a protocol&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:02.720 --> 00:03:09.040
or technology should work. When devices follow&nbsp;
vendor-neutral standards, devices of all types can&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:09.040 --> 00:03:15.040
communicate with each other. For example, an Apple&nbsp;
MacBook can access a website hosted on a Linux web&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:15.040 --> 00:03:20.560
server. And a PC running Windows can send an&nbsp;
email that can be read on a smartphone running&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:20.560 --> 00:03:28.000
Android. As long as the devices follow the same&nbsp;
standards, they can work together on the network.

00:03:28.000 --> 00:03:34.400
How did TCP/IP come about? Let’s cover a bit of&nbsp;
history. Early work on the computer networks that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:34.400 --> 00:03:40.960
would evolve into today’s Internet began in the&nbsp;
1960s, mainly in the US. The US Department of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:40.960 --> 00:03:48.480
Defense’s ARPA, Advanced Research Projects Agency,&nbsp;
funded ARPANET. It came online in 1969 to connect&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:48.480 --> 00:03:53.840
mainframes at universities and labs around the&nbsp;
country. Here’s a map showing ARPANET in the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:03:53.840 --> 00:04:00.720
1970s, connecting locations mostly around the east&nbsp;
and west coasts of the country. ARPANET originally&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:00.720 --> 00:04:08.720
used a protocol called NCP, the Network Control&nbsp;
Program. There was no TCP/IP in the early days.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:08.720 --> 00:04:14.560
In 1974, Vint Cerf and Bob Kahn, two of&nbsp;
the fathers of the modern Internet, began&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:14.560 --> 00:04:21.040
developing TCP, Transmission Control Program,&nbsp;
as an internetworking protocol. TCP went through&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:21.040 --> 00:04:26.560
a few revisions, and was later divided into two&nbsp;
protocols that are still used today: Transmission&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:26.560 --> 00:04:33.200
Control Protocol, TCP. Notice the name change from&nbsp;
“Program” to “Protocol”. And Internet Protocol,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:33.200 --> 00:04:39.600
IP. Together, these two protocols form the&nbsp;
foundation of the protocol suite widely known&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:39.600 --> 00:04:50.640
as TCP/IP today. And the ARPANET fully switched to&nbsp;
use TCP/IP on January 1st, 1983. Over time, TCP/IP&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:50.640 --> 00:04:55.440
became dominant over other vendor-proprietary&nbsp;
solutions at the time because it was published&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:04:55.440 --> 00:05:00.160
as a set of open standards that any vendor could&nbsp;
implement, and it could run over many different&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:00.160 --> 00:05:05.280
types of networks. And here we are several&nbsp;
decades later, still learning about TCP/IP.

00:05:08.400 --> 00:05:13.680
That’s enough history. Now who actually defines&nbsp;
these standards? Most networking standards are&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:13.680 --> 00:05:19.280
created by independent standards organizations,&nbsp;
not by a single vendor. Engineers from many&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:19.280 --> 00:05:24.160
different companies participate in the process.&nbsp;
When it comes to networking, there are two&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:24.160 --> 00:05:30.320
organizations you should be aware of. The first&nbsp;
one is the IEEE, the Institute of Electrical and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:30.320 --> 00:05:35.760
Electronics Engineers. I mentioned the IEEE in&nbsp;
the previous video when talking about Ethernet&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:35.760 --> 00:05:43.040
cables. The IEEE develops many of the technologies&nbsp;
we use on local area networks, such as Ethernet,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:43.040 --> 00:05:50.080
which is defined in the 802.3 set of standards.&nbsp;
The IEEE also develops Wi-Fi, which is defined&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:50.080 --> 00:05:57.360
in the 802.11 standards. These standards include&nbsp;
physical specifications like Ethernet cable types,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:05:57.360 --> 00:06:03.600
Wi-Fi radio frequency, and how to transmit signals&nbsp;
over the physical medium, whether a cable or a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:03.600 --> 00:06:09.440
radio wave. But they also specify how to format&nbsp;
messages to send them to another device over the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:09.440 --> 00:06:16.240
medium. Both are important topics that we’ll cover&nbsp;
in this course. The second standards group is the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:16.240 --> 00:06:23.360
IETF, the Internet Engineering Task Force. The&nbsp;
IETF is an open community that defines many of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:23.360 --> 00:06:33.040
the protocols used on the Internet. A few examples&nbsp;
are TCP, IP, UDP, HTTP, and DNS. If you don’t know&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:33.040 --> 00:06:39.840
these protocols yet, don’t worry: they’re all in&nbsp;
this course. The IETF publishes its standards in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:39.840 --> 00:06:46.080
documents called RFCs, Requests for Comments, all&nbsp;
of which are freely available on the Internet.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:46.720 --> 00:06:53.280
The IEEE and IETF create the standards, and then&nbsp;
vendors like Cisco implement them so that devices&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:53.280 --> 00:06:58.560
from different companies can work together. But&nbsp;
there are many different standards and protocols,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:06:58.560 --> 00:07:03.360
each solving a different part of the overall&nbsp;
communication problem. To make sense of them,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:03.360 --> 00:07:09.040
it helps to group their jobs into&nbsp;
layers, making a layered model.

00:07:09.040 --> 00:07:14.000
So let’s look at that layered model. Networks&nbsp;
do a lot of different jobs when they move data&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:14.000 --> 00:07:19.760
from one computer to another. Things like the&nbsp;
physical transmission of signals, local delivery&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:19.760 --> 00:07:25.680
of messages on a LAN, routing traffic between&nbsp;
networks, maintaining end-to-end conversations,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:25.680 --> 00:07:33.040
and the applications themselves. A model lets us&nbsp;
group related jobs into layers. Each layer has a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:33.040 --> 00:07:38.880
specific role, and each layer uses the services&nbsp;
of the layer below and provides services to the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:38.880 --> 00:07:45.280
layer above. We’ll come back to this idea&nbsp;
later. Protocols live mostly at one layer.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:45.280 --> 00:07:50.960
I say “mostly” because sometimes the lines are&nbsp;
blurred and it’s hard to categorize a protocol.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:50.960 --> 00:07:58.160
Some examples of protocols that we’ll look at&nbsp;
later are IP, TCP, and HTTP. Together they form&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:07:58.160 --> 00:08:04.240
a “stack” of protocols that work as a team, often&nbsp;
called the network stack. Here’s an example of a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:04.240 --> 00:08:12.720
protocol stack from RFC 791, which defines IP, the&nbsp;
Internet Protocol. It was published in 1981, but&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:12.720 --> 00:08:19.600
this is still the current standard we use today.&nbsp;
If you’re curious, do a Google search for RFC 791:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:19.600 --> 00:08:24.800
as I said in the previous slide, RFCs are freely&nbsp;
available online, although they can be quite&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:24.800 --> 00:08:31.200
dense reading. You don’t need to read them for the&nbsp;
CCNA. We can divide this stack into a few layers&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:31.200 --> 00:08:39.680
like this. At the top, we have the application&nbsp;
layer, with protocols like Telnet, FTP, and TFTP.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:39.680 --> 00:08:45.120
I won’t define these protocols now, but they’re&nbsp;
all covered in this course. Then below it, we&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:45.120 --> 00:08:53.040
have the Transport layer, with protocols like TCP&nbsp;
and UDP. Below that is the Internet layer. Here,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:53.040 --> 00:08:57.200
“Internet” doesn’t just mean THE Internet, the&nbsp;
public Internet you’re probably using to watch&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:08:57.200 --> 00:09:02.720
this video. It refers to an internetwork,&nbsp;
multiple networks connected together. That’s&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:02.720 --> 00:09:08.400
the real job of this layer. This is where we&nbsp;
find IP, which has two versions in use today:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:08.400 --> 00:09:16.000
IP version 4 and IP version 6, both important&nbsp;
CCNA topics. Finally, we have the Link layer,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:16.000 --> 00:09:21.280
including local network protocols like&nbsp;
Ethernet and Wi-Fi. Each of these layers,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:21.280 --> 00:09:27.680
and the protocols in them, plays a different&nbsp;
role in the network. This is the TCP/IP model,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:27.680 --> 00:09:33.520
at least one version of it. The model is a&nbsp;
description, not a law. For example, different&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:33.520 --> 00:09:38.880
textbooks and courses use slightly different&nbsp;
models, some with 4 layers, some with 5 layers,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:38.880 --> 00:09:46.640
and some with more. In this course I’ll use&nbsp;
a five-layer model that builds on this one.

00:09:46.640 --> 00:09:51.520
Before talking about networks specifically,&nbsp;
let’s use an analogy for this layered approach:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:51.520 --> 00:09:56.400
sending a letter to a friend via the post. I&nbsp;
don’t use analogies like this often because&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:09:56.400 --> 00:10:01.840
they can cause misunderstandings if you take them&nbsp;
too seriously, but I think this one is helpful.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:01.840 --> 00:10:06.560
On the left, you’re in your house. And on the&nbsp;
right, Bob and his wife are in their house,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:06.560 --> 00:10:12.000
with a couple of post offices between, connected&nbsp;
by roads. You write a letter, which is addressed&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:12.000 --> 00:10:18.000
to Bob. You then put the letter in an envelope&nbsp;
addressed to Bob’s house. Bob’s house is a bit&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:18.000 --> 00:10:22.640
far from where you live, so instead of driving&nbsp;
directly to his house, you deliver the envelope&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:22.640 --> 00:10:29.520
in your car to post office A, like this. Notice&nbsp;
the three different destinations. Your car is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:29.520 --> 00:10:35.440
going to post office A. The envelope inside your&nbsp;
car is going to Bob’s house. And the letter inside&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:35.440 --> 00:10:42.560
the envelope is going to Bob himself. Post office&nbsp;
A then moves the envelope to a truck and delivers&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:42.560 --> 00:10:48.960
it to post office B, like this. The truck’s&nbsp;
destination is post office B, but the envelope and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:48.960 --> 00:10:55.200
letter inside keep their original destinations.&nbsp;
Then, post office B moves the envelope to a new&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:10:55.200 --> 00:11:00.880
truck and delivers it to Bob’s house, like this.&nbsp;
Once again, this truck has a different destination&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:00.880 --> 00:11:06.240
from the previous truck: Bob’s house. The envelope&nbsp;
and letter inside still have their original&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:06.240 --> 00:11:12.240
destinations. The envelope is now delivered to&nbsp;
Bob’s house, opened, and the letter addressed to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:12.240 --> 00:11:18.800
Bob is read by him. So in this simple mail system,&nbsp;
different parts care about different things: the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:18.800 --> 00:11:25.040
message itself, who should read it, which house&nbsp;
it goes to, and how it moves along the route.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:25.040 --> 00:11:32.240
We can turn those roles into a layered model,&nbsp;
and then compare that model to how TCP/IP works.

00:11:32.240 --> 00:11:37.200
So, let’s build that model. Don’t worry about&nbsp;
remembering this model or the names of the layers:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:37.200 --> 00:11:42.880
it’s just an analogy for now. At the top we&nbsp;
have a content layer, the text of the letter:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:42.880 --> 00:11:49.200
what you actually want to say. I’ll call the next&nbsp;
layer the recipient layer: the “To: Bob” part,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:49.200 --> 00:11:54.560
indicating who inside the house should read the&nbsp;
letter. Below that is the address layer, which&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:11:54.560 --> 00:12:00.560
is the destination address of the house where&nbsp;
that person lives. Next is the local delivery&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:00.560 --> 00:12:05.520
layer, which handles moving the envelope to the&nbsp;
next stop on the path using cars and trucks:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:05.520 --> 00:12:11.440
from your house to post office A, then post&nbsp;
office B, then Bob’s house. With these four&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:11.440 --> 00:12:17.680
roles we already have a simple 4-layer model,&nbsp;
similar to the TCP/IP stack I showed before.&nbsp;

00:12:17.680 --> 00:12:22.080
But we can add one more layer at the&nbsp;
bottom. I’ll call it the infrastructure&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:22.080 --> 00:12:26.880
layer: the roads and other paths that&nbsp;
the vehicles travel on. But really,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:26.880 --> 00:12:32.640
these bottom two layers are related and always&nbsp;
work together. If traveling over ground,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:32.640 --> 00:12:37.840
local delivery uses a car or truck. If&nbsp;
traveling in the air, local delivery uses&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:37.840 --> 00:12:43.680
an airplane. If traveling by water, local&nbsp;
delivery uses a ship. And often the letter&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:43.680 --> 00:12:49.360
will travel over multiple kinds of paths in its&nbsp;
journey: ground, then air, then ground again,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:49.360 --> 00:12:54.800
for example. You can either think of these&nbsp;
bottom two layers as one combined delivery layer,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:12:54.800 --> 00:13:03.600
or split them into two layers. And that’s why some&nbsp;
networking models use 4 layers and some use 5.

00:13:03.600 --> 00:13:08.160
One of the benefits of a layered system like&nbsp;
this is how the layers work together, but&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:08.160 --> 00:13:14.720
remain separate. Each layer has its own job. They&nbsp;
work together to deliver the message, but each&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:14.720 --> 00:13:21.200
one focuses on its own task. The Content layer&nbsp;
focuses on the actual contents of the letter,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:21.200 --> 00:13:26.560
and that doesn’t change throughout the journey.&nbsp;
The Recipient layer focuses on the individual&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:26.560 --> 00:13:32.240
person who should receive the letter, and also&nbsp;
remains the same from start to finish. Likewise,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:32.240 --> 00:13:36.720
the Address layer focuses on the address of the&nbsp;
house or building to which the letter should be&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:36.720 --> 00:13:43.120
delivered, and that stays the same as well. The&nbsp;
Local Delivery layer focuses on getting the letter&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:43.120 --> 00:13:50.000
to the next stop in the route: post office A,&nbsp;
then post office B, and finally Bob’s house. The&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:50.000 --> 00:13:56.080
Infrastructure layer is the system of roads and&nbsp;
mail trucks that the delivery process relies on.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:13:56.080 --> 00:14:02.160
What happens inside one layer doesn’t change the&nbsp;
job of the other layers. For example, changing the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:02.160 --> 00:14:07.680
content of the letter doesn’t change the delivery&nbsp;
steps. And changing the delivery path doesn’t&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:07.680 --> 00:14:12.800
affect the letter itself. When you’re writing the&nbsp;
letter to Bob, you don’t have to think about how&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:12.800 --> 00:14:18.400
the postal service will go about delivering it. Of&nbsp;
course, that doesn’t mean the layers are entirely&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:18.400 --> 00:14:23.920
independent. For example, if you address the&nbsp;
letter to somewhere overseas, that will influence&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:23.920 --> 00:14:30.000
how it’s delivered. But that’s not your concern&nbsp;
as you write the letter. This separation of layers&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:30.000 --> 00:14:35.760
is true in our mail system model example, and&nbsp;
it’s true of networks as well. Now let’s replace&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:35.760 --> 00:14:44.240
letters with data and roads with networks, and&nbsp;
build the 5-layer TCP/IP model we’ll actually use.

00:14:44.240 --> 00:14:50.640
Here are the five layers of our mail system.&nbsp;
Let’s map them to the TCP/IP model. The Content&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:50.640 --> 00:14:56.960
layer is equivalent to the TCP/IP Application&nbsp;
layer. The Recipient layer maps to the Transport&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:14:56.960 --> 00:15:02.240
layer. The Address layer matches the Internet&nbsp;
layer. These are the same names I showed before&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:02.240 --> 00:15:08.160
for the TCP/IP model. But I’m going to use&nbsp;
a different name next. The Local Delivery&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:08.160 --> 00:15:13.040
layer matches what I’ll call the Local Network&nbsp;
layer. This is the layer used for delivering&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:13.040 --> 00:15:18.640
messages within a LAN, a local area network.&nbsp;
There are a few different names for this layer,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:18.640 --> 00:15:23.840
but I’ll go with “Local Network”. And finally&nbsp;
the Infrastructure layer is equivalent to the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:23.840 --> 00:15:29.360
Physical layer. At this point, these&nbsp;
names probably don’t mean much to you,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:29.360 --> 00:15:36.560
so next we’ll see how they actually work in&nbsp;
a real network between a client and a server.

00:15:36.560 --> 00:15:41.920
Here is a simple network I’ll use to demonstrate.&nbsp;
You’ve seen these icons before. On the left,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:41.920 --> 00:15:48.320
we have PC1, a client that will send a request&nbsp;
to SRV1, the server on the right. Between them&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:48.320 --> 00:15:57.360
are two routers, R1 and R2, and two switches: SW1&nbsp;
between PC1 and R1, and SW2 between R2 and SRV1.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:15:58.880 --> 00:16:04.960
PC1 is running a web client application; in&nbsp;
other words, a web browser such as Chrome.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:04.960 --> 00:16:11.120
SRV1 is running a couple of processes: a&nbsp;
web server and a file server. PC1’s user&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:11.120 --> 00:16:17.840
wants to access a web page hosted on SRV1, so&nbsp;
the web client on PC1, let’s say it’s Chrome,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:17.840 --> 00:16:23.040
needs to send a request to the web server&nbsp;
on SRV1. That’s the role of the application&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:23.040 --> 00:16:28.800
layer: it includes protocols for communication&nbsp;
between application processes and is responsible&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:28.800 --> 00:16:34.400
for creating and interpreting the data. But&nbsp;
there’s a problem: there are multiple processes&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:34.400 --> 00:16:41.280
running on SRV1: a web server process and a&nbsp;
file server process, and possibly more. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:41.280 --> 00:16:47.280
how can PC1 ensure that its request reaches&nbsp;
the correct process on SRV1? That’s the role&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:47.280 --> 00:16:54.560
of the Transport layer. Each process on SRV1&nbsp;
has an associated transport “port number”:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:16:54.560 --> 00:17:00.720
80 for the web server and 21 for the file server.&nbsp;
Don’t worry about the exact numbers for now;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:00.720 --> 00:17:05.680
that’s for later in the course. The important&nbsp;
point is that, to send the message to the web&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:05.680 --> 00:17:11.920
server, PC1 addresses it to port 80. Don’t&nbsp;
be confused by the name “port”; these aren’t&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:11.920 --> 00:17:17.360
physical ports like we looked at in the previous&nbsp;
lecture. Here, a port is just a number used to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:17.360 --> 00:17:23.360
identify a process running on a host. The role&nbsp;
of the Transport layer is to provide end-to-end&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:23.360 --> 00:17:29.520
communication between application processes, such&nbsp;
as the web browser on PC1 and the web server on&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:29.520 --> 00:17:35.440
SRV1, using port numbers. But we still have a&nbsp;
problem: even if the message is addressed to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:35.440 --> 00:17:41.360
the correct port on SRV1, we still have to make&nbsp;
sure the message reaches SRV1 in the first place.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:42.000 --> 00:17:50.480
SRV1 has an IP address for that purpose. For&nbsp;
example, let’s say its IP address is 10.1.1.1.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:50.480 --> 00:17:57.040
Again, don’t worry about the format of the address&nbsp;
itself yet; that’s a topic for another video. By&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:17:57.040 --> 00:18:02.800
addressing its message to SRV1’s IP address,&nbsp;
PC1 tells the routers in the path which host&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:02.800 --> 00:18:08.480
the message should be delivered to. That’s the&nbsp;
role of the Internet layer: it provides end-to-end&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:08.480 --> 00:18:14.160
communication between hosts, from the source host&nbsp;
to the destination host, using IP addresses and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:14.160 --> 00:18:20.880
routers. When you think of the Internet layer,&nbsp;
think “IP addresses and routers.” And “host”,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:20.880 --> 00:18:25.440
by the way, just means a device connected to&nbsp;
the network that can send and receive data,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:25.440 --> 00:18:32.400
such as PC1 and SRV1. So, we’re getting close&nbsp;
to achieving our goal of getting PC1’s request&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:32.400 --> 00:18:39.520
to SRV1, but we’re not quite there yet. There are&nbsp;
several devices between PC1 and SRV1, and we need&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:39.520 --> 00:18:45.040
to make sure the message is properly passed along&nbsp;
between them. That’s the role of the Local Network&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:45.040 --> 00:18:50.960
layer. Using protocols at this layer, such as&nbsp;
Ethernet, each device sends the message to the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:18:50.960 --> 00:19:00.000
next device on the local network: PC1 to R1 via&nbsp;
SW1,R1 forwards the message to R2. And finally,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:00.000 --> 00:19:07.840
R2 forwards the message to SRV1 via SW2. The Local&nbsp;
Network layer provides hop-to-hop delivery within&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:07.840 --> 00:19:14.320
a local network using MAC addresses and switches.&nbsp;
I’ll explain the term “hop-to-hop” more in a bit,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:14.320 --> 00:19:19.920
and MAC addresses are a topic for another video.&nbsp;
Looking at this diagram, you might wonder about&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:19.920 --> 00:19:26.160
the role of the switches; they connect devices in&nbsp;
a LAN and pass messages between them. We’ll look&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:26.160 --> 00:19:31.200
at how that works in detail in future&nbsp;
videos. Okay, and last but not least,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:31.200 --> 00:19:36.320
we have the Physical layer: all of these cables&nbsp;
connecting the devices, and the transceivers on&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:36.320 --> 00:19:43.120
the devices that transmit and receive signals. The&nbsp;
Physical layer sends bits as electrical, optical,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:43.120 --> 00:19:49.520
or radio signals over the physical medium.&nbsp;
Electrical signals over copper UTP cables,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:19:49.520 --> 00:19:57.840
optical signals over fiber-optic cables, and&nbsp;
radio signals over wireless Wi-Fi connections.

00:19:57.840 --> 00:20:01.600
We’ve covered the role of each layer.&nbsp;
But now let’s go from the bottom up,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:01.600 --> 00:20:07.440
from the Physical layer to the Application layer,&nbsp;
and look at a few more details. The Physical&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:07.440 --> 00:20:12.800
layer, also called “Layer 1”, is responsible&nbsp;
for sending and receiving bits as electrical,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:12.800 --> 00:20:18.800
optical, or radio signals over the medium.&nbsp;
It defines things like cables, connectors,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:18.800 --> 00:20:24.800
signal levels, and link speeds: all of the&nbsp;
physical aspects of communication. Examples&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:24.800 --> 00:20:31.200
include copper UTP and fiber-optic cables, Wi-Fi&nbsp;
radios and antennas, and network interface cards,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:31.200 --> 00:20:38.720
also called NICs. Here are a few examples: UTP&nbsp;
ports and a cable on the left, fiber-optic in the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:38.720 --> 00:20:44.640
middle, and an image of a NIC on the right. Each&nbsp;
network interface has a NIC like this inside of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:44.640 --> 00:20:50.640
the device. The physical aspects of transmitting&nbsp;
data are very complex, involving a lot of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:50.640 --> 00:20:56.080
electrical or optical engineering. Fortunately,&nbsp;
network engineers typically don’t have to know&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:20:56.080 --> 00:21:02.240
the low-level details of how it all works. So,&nbsp;
that’s the Physical layer: Layer 1 of our TCP/IP&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:02.240 --> 00:21:07.520
model. In some models this layer is combined&nbsp;
with the next layer, but I think it’s useful&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:07.520 --> 00:21:14.960
to differentiate between the physical concerns&nbsp;
like these and the logical aspects of Layer 2.

00:21:14.960 --> 00:21:20.640
Next, we have the Local Network layer, Layer&nbsp;
2. This layer provides hop-to-hop delivery of&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:20.640 --> 00:21:27.040
messages on a local network. So, what exactly&nbsp;
is a “hop”? A hop is one step along the path&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:27.040 --> 00:21:34.320
between two devices: from one router or host,&nbsp;
to the next router or host in the path. When PC1&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:34.320 --> 00:21:42.000
sends a message to SRV1, how many hops are there?&nbsp;
The first hop is from PC1 to R1. The second hop&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:42.000 --> 00:21:50.240
is from R1 to R2. And the third hop is from R2 to&nbsp;
SRV1, so three hops in total. Switches don’t count&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:50.240 --> 00:21:56.720
as hops: a switch just extends the local network,&nbsp;
allowing multiple devices to connect. To keep the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:21:56.720 --> 00:22:02.080
diagram simple I only show one host connected to&nbsp;
each of the switches, but there could be many more&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:02.080 --> 00:22:08.400
connected, like this. The switch allows them all&nbsp;
to connect to the same local area network. We’ll&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:08.400 --> 00:22:13.280
look at switches and LANs in detail in later&nbsp;
videos, so don’t worry about them for now.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:13.840 --> 00:22:21.920
Layer 2 uses MAC, Media Access Control, addresses&nbsp;
to identify interfaces. Each device connected to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:21.920 --> 00:22:27.920
a LAN has a unique MAC address for that&nbsp;
specific interface. Since R1 and R2 have&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:27.920 --> 00:22:34.080
multiple interfaces connected to the network,&nbsp;
let’s add some simple interface labels. G1, for&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:34.080 --> 00:22:40.880
GigabitEthernet1, and G2, for GigabitEthernet2,&nbsp;
meaning these interfaces operate at a speed of 1&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:40.880 --> 00:22:47.600
gigabit per second. PC1 sends the message&nbsp;
to the MAC address of R1’s G1 interface,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:47.600 --> 00:22:54.320
its NIC. That’s the interface that will receive&nbsp;
PC1’s message. R1 sends the message to the MAC&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:22:54.320 --> 00:23:00.400
address of R2’s G1 interface. And R2 sends&nbsp;
the message to the MAC address of SRV1’s&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:00.400 --> 00:23:06.560
interface. Once again, we’ll cover MAC addresses&nbsp;
in another video when we learn about switches.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:06.560 --> 00:23:13.040
The key protocols at this layer that you should&nbsp;
know for the CCNA are Ethernet and Wi-Fi. Others&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:13.040 --> 00:23:20.400
exist, of course, but these are by far the&nbsp;
most commonly used Layer-2 protocols today.

00:23:20.400 --> 00:23:25.760
Next up we have the Internet layer, which&nbsp;
is Layer 3 of our model. This layer provides&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:25.760 --> 00:23:31.760
end-to-end delivery between hosts across multiple&nbsp;
networks. We call it “end-to-end” because it&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:31.760 --> 00:23:37.040
focuses on getting the message from the source&nbsp;
host all the way to the final destination host,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:37.040 --> 00:23:42.000
instead of worrying about each individual&nbsp;
hop in the middle. Remember, “Internet”&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:42.000 --> 00:23:48.560
means “internetwork”, between networks. It uses&nbsp;
IP addresses to identify hosts in the network,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:48.560 --> 00:23:57.520
kind of like a home address. In our example, SRV1&nbsp;
has the IP address 10.1.1.1. So when PC1 sends&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:23:57.520 --> 00:24:05.280
a message to SRV1, it addresses the message to&nbsp;
SRV1’s IP address. Routers operate mainly at this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:05.280 --> 00:24:10.240
layer, using the message’s destination address to&nbsp;
forward the message toward its final destination&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:10.240 --> 00:24:16.560
host. There are a few protocols at this layer&nbsp;
that you’ll learn about for the CCNA: IP,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:16.560 --> 00:24:23.360
both version 4 and version 6, and ICMP,&nbsp;
the Internet Control Message Protocol.

00:24:24.720 --> 00:24:30.480
Next is Layer 4, the Transport layer. This&nbsp;
layer provides end-to-end communication between&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:30.480 --> 00:24:37.040
application processes. And why is that needed?&nbsp;
Well, in our example, our server, SRV1, provides&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:37.040 --> 00:24:44.160
multiple services. It’s running a web server and&nbsp;
a file server, and perhaps other services. If SRV1&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:44.160 --> 00:24:49.600
receives a message, it needs a way to know which&nbsp;
of these services should receive the message.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:49.600 --> 00:24:55.760
This can also be called “process-to-process”&nbsp;
or “service-to-service” communication. This&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:24:55.760 --> 00:25:01.520
layer uses port numbers to identify the processes&nbsp;
on each host, such as port 80 for the web server&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:01.520 --> 00:25:08.800
and port 21 for the file server. So, when the web&nbsp;
client on PC1 wants to send a request to the web&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:08.800 --> 00:25:15.520
server running on SRV1, it addresses the message&nbsp;
to port 80. And if PC1 wanted to access the file&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:15.520 --> 00:25:21.600
server instead, it would address its messages&nbsp;
to port 21. The Transport layer allows hosts&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:21.600 --> 00:25:27.680
to differentiate between these different streams&nbsp;
of data. Layer 4 runs mainly on the communicating&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:27.680 --> 00:25:35.680
hosts, PC1 and SRV1. Routers normally operate&nbsp;
based on IP, Layer 3, not on Transport-layer&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:35.680 --> 00:25:41.040
information. There are exceptions of course,&nbsp;
but that’s a topic for later in the course.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:41.680 --> 00:25:48.400
Layer 4 is primarily a conversation between the&nbsp;
two communicating hosts. There are a few protocols&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:48.400 --> 00:25:55.920
used at this layer. The two most prominent are&nbsp;
UDP, User Datagram Protocol, and TCP, Transmission&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:25:55.920 --> 00:26:03.760
Control Protocol. They both offer some different&nbsp;
features, and we’ll cover them in this course.

00:26:03.760 --> 00:26:09.040
Finally, we have layer 5: the Application&nbsp;
layer. This is where network communications&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:09.040 --> 00:26:14.160
meet applications. Small side note:&nbsp;
this layer is usually called “Layer&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:14.160 --> 00:26:20.960
7”. I’ll explain why later when we talk about&nbsp;
another model, the OSI model. The Application&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:20.960 --> 00:26:26.880
layer defines how application processes&nbsp;
format, send, and interpret data. So,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:26.880 --> 00:26:31.840
when Chrome on PC1 sends a request&nbsp;
to the web server process on SRV1,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:31.840 --> 00:26:37.680
it uses an Application-layer protocol such&nbsp;
as HTTP to format and send the message,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:37.680 --> 00:26:43.760
and that same protocol tells the web server how&nbsp;
to interpret the message it receives. Protocols&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:43.760 --> 00:26:50.400
at this layer define message formats and rules&nbsp;
for specific tasks. Here are a few examples. For&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:50.400 --> 00:26:58.560
browsing web pages, we use HTTP, or more often&nbsp;
its secure version, HTTPS. For file transfers,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:26:58.560 --> 00:27:06.640
we can use FTP, TFTP, or another similar&nbsp;
protocol. And email uses its own protocols, too.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:06.640 --> 00:27:11.920
Don’t worry about the specific protocols or their&nbsp;
names at this point, right now we’re just talking&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:11.920 --> 00:27:18.400
big concepts. Network infrastructure devices&nbsp;
like routers and switches typically don’t care&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:18.400 --> 00:27:23.760
about Application-layer details. This is too&nbsp;
high-level for them. They just move messages&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:23.760 --> 00:27:30.240
across the network. Only the communicating&nbsp;
hosts, PC1 and SRV1 in this case, actually&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:30.240 --> 00:27:36.560
look at and interpret the Application-layer&nbsp;
data. Now that we’ve seen what each layer does,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:36.560 --> 00:27:42.240
how does a single message actually include all of&nbsp;
this information at once? Let’s see how the layers&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:42.240 --> 00:27:49.680
combine into a stack and how data moves through&nbsp;
them using encapsulation and decapsulation.

00:27:49.680 --> 00:27:54.960
To show how encapsulation and decapsulation&nbsp;
work, let’s simplify the network, making it a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:27:54.960 --> 00:28:01.520
direct connection between PC1 and SRV1. First,&nbsp;
the Application layer prepares the data to be&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:01.520 --> 00:28:08.160
sent over the network, for example an HTTP request&nbsp;
that Chrome on PC1 sends to a web server running&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:08.160 --> 00:28:16.000
on SRV1. As the message moves down the stack, each&nbsp;
layer encapsulates the data with a header that&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:16.000 --> 00:28:22.560
contains the information needed by that layer.&nbsp;
For example, the source and destination addresses:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:22.560 --> 00:28:29.360
Layer 4 port numbers, layer 3 IP addresses, and&nbsp;
Layer 2 MAC addresses, among other information.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:30.000 --> 00:28:35.200
So first, the Transport layer encapsulates&nbsp;
the data with its header, the Layer 4 header,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:35.200 --> 00:28:40.720
with source and destination port numbers&nbsp;
and other information. Then the Internet&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:40.720 --> 00:28:47.200
layer adds its header with source and destination&nbsp;
IP addresses. Then, Layer 2 encapsulates the data&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:47.200 --> 00:28:52.640
with both a header and a trailer. The trailer&nbsp;
is used by the receiving device to check for&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:52.640 --> 00:28:58.960
transmission errors. We’ll look at this in&nbsp;
more detail in a later video about Ethernet.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:28:58.960 --> 00:29:03.520
Finally, the Physical layer transmits the&nbsp;
bits as signals over the physical medium,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:03.520 --> 00:29:08.800
which is an Ethernet cable in this case. I’m&nbsp;
showing the message in order from left to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:08.800 --> 00:29:17.360
right here. So the Layer 2 header is transmitted&nbsp;
first, and Layer 2 trailer is transmitted last.

00:29:17.360 --> 00:29:23.600
So that was the encapsulation process, now let’s&nbsp;
look at decapsulation. The receiving device&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:23.600 --> 00:29:29.680
receives the message as a stream of bits at layer&nbsp;
1. Layer 1 simply passes those bits up to the next&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:29.680 --> 00:29:35.520
layer. Now it’s up to the other layers to&nbsp;
interpret those bits. The device examines the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:35.520 --> 00:29:41.440
information in the Layer 2 header and trailer, and&nbsp;
then removes them. This is called “decapsulation”,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:41.440 --> 00:29:48.800
or sometimes “de-encapsulation”. The decapsulation&nbsp;
process continues up the stack. So, Layer&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:48.800 --> 00:29:55.600
3 examines and removes the Layer 3 header. Then&nbsp;
Layer 4 examines and removes the Layer 4 header,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:29:55.600 --> 00:30:01.440
and the data is delivered to the Application&nbsp;
layer. Now the application processes the data and,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:01.440 --> 00:30:06.640
if needed, generates a response that goes back&nbsp;
down the stack, and is then transmitted back to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:06.640 --> 00:30:15.920
PC1. So, that’s the decapsulation process, which&nbsp;
is basically the encapsulation process in reverse.

00:30:15.920 --> 00:30:21.120
Each device has its own network stack.&nbsp;
A message from PC1 goes down its stack,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:21.120 --> 00:30:25.760
crosses the wire, and then goes up SRV1’s&nbsp;
stack where the Application layer processes&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:25.760 --> 00:30:31.600
it. The response does the same thing in the&nbsp;
opposite direction. It goes down SRV1’s stack,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:31.600 --> 00:30:36.720
is sent over the wire to PC1, and then goes&nbsp;
up PC1’s stack where the data is interpreted&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:36.720 --> 00:30:42.720
by the application. In a real network there are&nbsp;
switches, routers, and other devices between the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:42.720 --> 00:30:47.920
hosts. That adds more steps to the delivery&nbsp;
process, just like the mail system example,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:47.920 --> 00:30:53.920
where the letter is moved between cars and trucks.&nbsp;
But the overall flow is still the same: each&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:30:53.920 --> 00:31:00.160
host sends the message down its stack, across the&nbsp;
network, and up the other host’s stack. We’ll look&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:00.160 --> 00:31:07.520
at how those intermediate devices - the routers&nbsp;
and switches - handle messages in later videos.

00:31:07.520 --> 00:31:12.160
Now that we’ve seen how encapsulation and&nbsp;
decapsulation work, let’s look at what to call&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:12.160 --> 00:31:18.480
these messages. At each stage in the encapsulation&nbsp;
and decapsulation process, there is a name given&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:18.480 --> 00:31:25.760
to the message. The combination of data and a&nbsp;
Layer 4 header is called a segment when using TCP,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:25.760 --> 00:31:33.840
or a datagram when using UDP. Remember that point:&nbsp;
TCP creates segments, and UDP creates datagrams.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:33.840 --> 00:31:38.800
This difference has to do with how TCP and UDP&nbsp;
treat the data, but we don’t need those details&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:38.800 --> 00:31:46.480
yet. The combination of a segment or datagram and&nbsp;
a Layer 3 header is called a packet. “Packet” is&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:46.480 --> 00:31:51.520
the most common term we use when talking about&nbsp;
messages being sent over a network, but strictly&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:51.520 --> 00:31:57.520
speaking it refers to the message at this stage in&nbsp;
the process. Finally, the combination of a packet&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:31:57.520 --> 00:32:02.880
and a Layer 2 header and trailer is called&nbsp;
a frame. This is what is actually sent over&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:02.880 --> 00:32:08.400
the wire. You’ll never see a packet, segment,&nbsp;
or datagram travelling over the wire itself;&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:08.400 --> 00:32:14.080
they are always sent inside a frame. We can also&nbsp;
use alternative names to describe the message at&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:14.080 --> 00:32:21.840
each stage, using the term protocol data unit,&nbsp;
or PDU. A segment or datagram is a Layer 4 PDU,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:21.840 --> 00:32:33.360
or L4PDU. A packet is a Layer 3 PDU, or L3PDU. And&nbsp;
a frame is a Layer 2 PDU, or L2PDU. Both names are&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:33.360 --> 00:32:39.040
common, so I recommend knowing both. And there’s&nbsp;
one more important term to learn. The contents&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:39.040 --> 00:32:44.160
of each PDU, that is everything encapsulated by&nbsp;
the layer’s header and trailer, are called the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:44.160 --> 00:32:51.760
payload. So, at Layer 4 a segment or datagram’s&nbsp;
payload is the application data itself. At Layer&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:51.760 --> 00:32:58.160
3, a packet’s payload is a segment or datagram,&nbsp;
including the Layer 4 header and the data. And at&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:32:58.160 --> 00:33:05.200
Layer 2, a frame’s payload is a packet, including&nbsp;
the Layer 3 and Layer 4 headers and the data. Just&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:05.200 --> 00:33:13.200
remember that the payload is what’s inside the&nbsp;
PDU, not including that layer’s header or trailer.

00:33:13.200 --> 00:33:17.840
Finally, let’s talk about how these layers&nbsp;
interact with each other. I’ve replaced the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:17.840 --> 00:33:23.200
generic layer names with examples of common&nbsp;
protocols. Also note the distinction between&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:23.200 --> 00:33:29.120
Layer 2 Ethernet, which defines MAC addressing&nbsp;
and frames, and Ethernet at the physical layer,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:29.120 --> 00:33:34.480
which defines the signaling and physical&nbsp;
media. Each layer in the stack provides a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:34.480 --> 00:33:40.480
service to the layer above it, and is serviced by&nbsp;
the layer below it. This is called adjacent-layer&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:40.480 --> 00:33:47.360
interaction. For example, Layer 4 provides a&nbsp;
service to Layer 5 by delivering data to the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:47.360 --> 00:33:53.680
correct application using port numbers. Layer&nbsp;
3 provides a service to Layer 4 by delivering&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:33:53.680 --> 00:34:00.080
segments and datagrams to the correct destination&nbsp;
host using IP addresses. Layer 2 provides a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:00.080 --> 00:34:06.160
service to Layer 3 by delivering packets to&nbsp;
the next hop using MAC addresses. And Layer&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:06.160 --> 00:34:11.840
1 provides a service to Layer 2 by sending and&nbsp;
receiving the frame’s bits as electrical, optical,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:11.840 --> 00:34:20.160
or radio signals over the physical medium. Each&nbsp;
layer relies on the layer below it to do its job.

00:34:20.160 --> 00:34:26.000
There’s also a related concept. Each layer&nbsp;
communicates with the same layer on other devices,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:26.000 --> 00:34:31.840
and this is called same-layer interaction.&nbsp;
For example, the Application layer on one host&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:31.840 --> 00:34:37.360
sends data to the Application layer on the other&nbsp;
host. A segment or datagram is addressed to the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:37.360 --> 00:34:43.200
Layer 4 port number of the correct application&nbsp;
on the destination host. A packet is addressed&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:43.200 --> 00:34:49.040
to the Layer 3 IP address of the destination&nbsp;
host. A frame is addressed to the Layer 2 MAC&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:49.040 --> 00:34:54.480
address of the next hop. And signals sent&nbsp;
out of a physical port are received by a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:54.480 --> 00:34:59.520
physical port on the connected device.&nbsp;
This layered cooperation - within each&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:34:59.520 --> 00:35:05.680
device and between devices - is what&nbsp;
makes network communication possible.

00:35:05.680 --> 00:35:10.560
Just like in our mail system example, the&nbsp;
separation of layers is key to how networks&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:10.560 --> 00:35:17.360
work. Each layer has its own job and provides a&nbsp;
specific service to the layers above. Because the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:17.360 --> 00:35:23.440
layers are modular, we can swap protocols at one&nbsp;
layer without changing the others. For example,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:23.440 --> 00:35:30.720
instead of a web page exchange using HTTP and&nbsp;
TCP, maybe it’s a file exchange using TFTP,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:30.720 --> 00:35:36.720
Trivial File Transfer Protocol, over UDP.&nbsp;
The lower layers in the stack can use IP&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:36.720 --> 00:35:40.160
and Ethernet without worrying about&nbsp;
the details of what the upper layers&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:40.160 --> 00:35:46.640
are doing. And if instead of a wired Ethernet&nbsp;
connection it’s a wireless Wi-Fi connection,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:46.640 --> 00:35:51.840
Layers 1 and 2 can change to Wi-Fi without&nbsp;
affecting the upper layers. As long as each&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:51.840 --> 00:35:57.360
layer keeps its “contract” with the layers above&nbsp;
and below, we can improve or replace protocols at&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:35:57.360 --> 00:36:02.960
different layers without redesigning everything.&nbsp;
That flexibility is one of the main benefits of a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:02.960 --> 00:36:08.240
layered model. Now that we’ve built&nbsp;
this 5-layer TCP/IP model, let’s see&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:08.240 --> 00:36:15.200
how it compares to other models you’ll see in&nbsp;
other courses and books, like the OSI model.

00:36:15.200 --> 00:36:19.200
You might have heard of the OSI model&nbsp;
before. If you’ve studied IT before,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:19.200 --> 00:36:24.640
you almost certainly have. As I said at the&nbsp;
beginning of this video, TCP/IP development&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:24.640 --> 00:36:31.840
started in the 1970s, with work on ARPANET and&nbsp;
the early TCP/IP specifications. But in the late&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:31.840 --> 00:36:39.040
1970s and 1980s, the International Organization&nbsp;
for Standardization, the ISO, designed a 7-layer&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:39.040 --> 00:36:45.440
model called OSI, Open Systems Interconnection,&nbsp;
and a matching protocol suite. The goal was to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:45.440 --> 00:36:50.480
create international, vendor-neutral networking&nbsp;
standards that could unify existing proprietary&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:50.480 --> 00:36:56.960
stacks and potentially replace TCP/IP as the&nbsp;
vendor-neutral choice. Here is that model,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:36:56.960 --> 00:37:04.320
with seven layers from top to bottom: Application,&nbsp;
Presentation, Session, Transport, Network, Data&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:37:04.320 --> 00:37:10.480
Link, and Physical. Governments, including the&nbsp;
US, promoted OSI as the preferred or recommended&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:37:10.480 --> 00:37:17.440
stack for new deployments. And for a while many&nbsp;
people thought that OSI was the future. But OSI&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:37:17.440 --> 00:37:22.400
protocols ended up being developed too late and&nbsp;
were too complex, and they never gained the same&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:37:22.400 --> 00:37:28.480
level of deployment as TCP/IP. I wasn’t around&nbsp;
at the time, but my understanding is that this&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:37:28.480 --> 00:37:33.680
was largely due to the bureaucratic nature of&nbsp;
the approach to developing OSI and its protocol&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:37:33.680 --> 00:37:40.400
stack. The process was very top-down: committees&nbsp;
designed the protocols in detail, and vendors were&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:37:40.400 --> 00:37:47.440
expected to implement them exactly as specified.&nbsp;
TCP/IP used a more bottom-up approach. In the end,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:37:47.440 --> 00:37:54.000
TCP/IP won in the real world, although some&nbsp;
OSI technologies are still used. Today,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:37:54.000 --> 00:38:00.480
almost all networks use the TCP/IP protocol stack,&nbsp;
but the 7-layer OSI model survives as a reference&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:38:00.480 --> 00:38:06.320
and teaching model, and as a common way to talk&nbsp;
about layers. Actually, most networking resources&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:38:06.320 --> 00:38:12.560
use a 5-layer model like the one I covered in this&nbsp;
video, but with names borrowed from the OSI model.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:38:12.560 --> 00:38:19.280
Here is that 5-layer model. I foreshadowed this&nbsp;
earlier in the video, but this is why the TCP/IP&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:38:19.280 --> 00:38:26.480
Application layer is often called Layer 7: because&nbsp;
the Application layer is Layer 7 of the OSI model.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:38:26.480 --> 00:38:30.960
I’ve also highlighted the two layer names that&nbsp;
are different from the model I introduced:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:38:30.960 --> 00:38:37.760
Layer 3 is called the Network layer, and&nbsp;
Layer 2 is called the Data Link layer.

00:38:37.760 --> 00:38:42.480
And to make things even more confusing, here’s&nbsp;
a selection from Wikipedia of different models&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:38:42.480 --> 00:38:48.240
proposed by various authors. Here we have the&nbsp;
four-layer TCP/IP model I showed at the beginning&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:38:48.240 --> 00:38:55.600
of this video. Here is the seven-layer OSI model.&nbsp;
And the adapted five-layer model I just showed in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:38:55.600 --> 00:39:01.040
the previous slide. When you see all of these&nbsp;
variations, you might wonder which model and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:39:01.040 --> 00:39:06.240
which names you should actually learn. Of course,&nbsp;
I recommend the five-layer model I presented in&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:39:06.240 --> 00:39:12.240
this video, because I think its names best match&nbsp;
the job of each layer. But this five-layer model&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:39:12.240 --> 00:39:18.160
shown here is probably the most common in books&nbsp;
and other resources. The only differences from my&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:39:18.160 --> 00:39:23.360
model are that Layer 3 is called the Network&nbsp;
layer and Layer 2 is called the Data Link&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:39:23.360 --> 00:39:28.560
layer. In the end, it’s not that important:&nbsp;
in practice people usually just refer to&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:39:28.560 --> 00:39:35.680
“Layer 2” and “Layer 3”, and you won’t be&nbsp;
quizzed about layer names on the CCNA exam.

00:39:35.680 --> 00:39:40.160
Before wrapping up, let’s review the key&nbsp;
concepts from this video. I won’t explain&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:39:40.160 --> 00:39:45.040
everything again here; I’ll just point out what&nbsp;
you should focus on as you review. The first is,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:39:45.040 --> 00:39:50.400
of course, the TCP/IP model itself. You should&nbsp;
know the general purpose of each of these&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:39:50.400 --> 00:39:57.040
layers. I also recommend knowing these more&nbsp;
commonly used names borrowed from the OSI model.

00:39:57.040 --> 00:40:02.000
It’s also important to understand the&nbsp;
encapsulation and decapsulation processes.&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:40:02.000 --> 00:40:05.360
In encapsulation, the sending&nbsp;
host adds headers, and a trailer,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:40:05.360 --> 00:40:10.480
to the data to prepare it for transmission&nbsp;
over the physical medium. In decapsulation,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:40:10.480 --> 00:40:17.440
the receiving host removes the headers and trailer&nbsp;
layer by layer until it gets to the data inside.

00:40:17.440 --> 00:40:23.440
You should also know the names of the different&nbsp;
PDUs, protocol data units. The Layer 4 PDU is a&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:40:23.440 --> 00:40:30.960
segment when using TCP and a datagram when using&nbsp;
UDP. The Layer 3 PDU is called a packet. And the&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:40:30.960 --> 00:40:36.720
Layer 2 PDU is called a frame; the frame is what&nbsp;
is actually transmitted over the physical medium.

00:40:36.720 --> 00:40:42.080
And finally, you should understand adjacent-layer&nbsp;
interaction and same-layer interaction. These&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:40:42.080 --> 00:40:45.920
concepts describe how the different layers&nbsp;
work together within each host and with&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:40:45.920 --> 00:40:52.800
their counterparts on other devices to achieve&nbsp;
communication between applications over a network.

00:40:52.800 --> 00:40:58.400
That’s all for this video on the TCP/IP model. By&nbsp;
now you should have a mental picture of the five&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:40:58.400 --> 00:41:03.200
layers, what each one is responsible for, and&nbsp;
how they work together using encapsulation and&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:41:03.200 --> 00:41:08.480
decapsulation. You don’t need to remember every&nbsp;
example or every historical detail; the important&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:41:08.480 --> 00:41:14.880
thing is that you know the layers, their general&nbsp;
roles, and the idea of PDUs and layer interaction.

00:41:14.880 --> 00:41:19.760
We’ll keep coming back to this model throughout&nbsp;
the course. You’ll hear the terms “Layer 1”,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:41:19.760 --> 00:41:25.120
“Layer 2”, “Layer 3”, and so on many times.&nbsp;
As we dive into topics like Ethernet,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:41:25.120 --> 00:41:30.000
IP addressing, TCP, and routing, you’ll be&nbsp;
able to place each new concept at the right&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:41:30.000 --> 00:41:33.600
layer and see how it fits into&nbsp;
the bigger picture. Just remember,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:41:33.600 --> 00:41:38.880
this is a model, not a law. Real protocols&nbsp;
don’t always fit neatly into a single layer,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:41:38.880 --> 00:41:43.600
and that’s okay. The model is just a tool to help&nbsp;
you think about what’s happening in the network.

00:41:43.600 --> 00:41:47.680
If you’d like a structured companion to&nbsp;
these videos, I’ve also written two books:&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:41:47.680 --> 00:41:53.840
Acing the CCNA Exam Volume 1 and Volume 2. They&nbsp;
go into more detail than I can fit in the videos,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:41:53.840 --> 00:41:58.560
and include hundreds of diagrams and practice&nbsp;
questions. I honestly think they’re my best&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:41:58.560 --> 00:42:03.360
work when it comes to teaching the CCNA. If&nbsp;
you’re interested, you can find them on Amazon,&nbsp;&nbsp;

00:42:03.360 --> 00:42:08.000
or use the links in the description to get them&nbsp;
directly from the publisher. Thanks for watching.

00:42:08.640 --> 00:42:12.720
Before we wrap up, I want to say a quick thank&nbsp;
you to the channel members whose names you see&nbsp;&nbsp;

